This paper deals with distributed computing models and algorithms, specifically focusing on set consensus. The paper discusses the decidability of certain tasks in restricted classes of models, which falls under the category of distributed computing (cs.DC). The use of dynamic programming and optimization algorithms suggests a connection to data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) and logic in computer science (cs.LO). The paper also discusses the power of a read-write model, which could be relevant to computational complexity (cs.CC) and control systems (cs.SY).
